Got the following sample code from https://github.com/airbnb/javascript/tree/master/react#methods

```
  // bad
  class extends React.Component {
    onClickDiv(param, event) {
      // do stuff
    }

    render() {
      return <div onClick={this.onClickDiv.bind(this, param)} />
    }
  }
```

How achieve this in the following good practice?

```
// good
  class extends React.Component {
    constructor(props) {
      super(props);

      this.onClickDiv = this.onClickDiv.bind(this);
    }

    onClickDiv() {
      // do stuff
    }

    render() {
      return <div onClick={this.onClickDiv} />
    }
  }
```

This is spawned as a result of a Twitter conversation with @ljharb.

Some JSCS rules are not covered by the ESLint rule set. As you'll see from the code provided below, style was an issue and the ESLint rule set alone was not enough.

